# Verification Plan: __PROJECT_NAME__

> Updated on: __DATE__
>
> Define how correctness will be proven before large-scale implementation starts.

## 1. Test Goals

- Prevent contract breakage, authentication/validation regressions, and integration failures early
- Prioritize the core HTTP paths that callers will integrate first

## 2. Test Layers

| Layer | Goal | Coverage | Tool / Method |
|---|---|---|---|
| Unit | Verify pure business rules | parameter rules, state transitions, error mapping | [TBD, for example a unit test framework] |
| Integration | Verify interface and dependency collaboration | handlers, storage, external services, or messaging systems | [TBD, for example API integration tests] |
| E2E | Verify real HTTP contracts | requests, responses, status codes, auth headers, error structures | [TBD, for example API end-to-end tests] |

## 3. Requirement-to-Test Mapping

| Test ID | Requirement | Test Type | Core Assertion |
|---|---|---|---|
| `TEST-001` | `FR-001` | E2E | Callers receive stable success responses and core resource state when following the contract |
| `TEST-002` | `FR-002` | Integration | Invalid input, auth failure, and dependency errors all return the shared error structure |

Requirements:

- Every high-priority `FR-*` maps to at least one automated test
- If a requirement cannot yet be verified automatically, document why and what the fallback verification is

## 4. First Red Tests

1. A valid request cannot create or query the core resource
2. Missing auth or invalid input does not return the shared error structure
3. An upstream timeout leaks internal failure details or returns unstable status codes

## 5. Test Data and Fixtures

- Prepare minimal valid requests, out-of-range requests, and conflict requests
- Prepare reusable fixtures for databases, caches, external APIs, or messaging systems

## 6. Regression Strategy

- All externally exposed APIs must keep contract regression coverage
- Any change to auth, validation, or error models must add corresponding regression tests
- Changes involving data-model migration, status-code changes, or integration boundaries require a full regression pass

## 7. Execution Guidance

- Start with the failing test for the smallest read/write endpoint
- Prioritize endpoints that are exposed first to callers and failure modes that are hardest to roll back
- If the test framework is not selected yet, write the test idea and assertions first, then choose tools later

## 8. Definition of Completion

- Every high-priority requirement has at least one automated verification path
- Critical failure scenarios are covered
- Bug fixes include regression tests
- Test commands can be run repeatedly with stable results
